WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6-Mute English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello, this is 6-Minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Neil.

4
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.000
And I'm Beth.

5
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:18.000
You may have one or know someone who does. And at one time you've been one yourself.

6
00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:21.000
I'm talking about toddlers.

7
00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:26.000
A toddler is a young child, usually between two and four years old,

8
00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:29.000
who is learning to walk or toddler.

9
00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:35.000
It's an important stage in a child's development as they learn to move and understand the world around them.

10
00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:38.000
It's also known as the Terrible Toos.

11
00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:42.000
When toddlers can't do the things they want to, they experience frustration,

12
00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:47.000
which often leads to tantrums, a sudden and noisy outburst of anger.

13
00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:53.000
We've probably all seen the tears and screams when a young child can't have what they want.

14
00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:56.000
Yes, the famous temper tantrums.

15
00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:02.000
But being a toddler is also an exciting time as a child's personality starts to develop.

16
00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:05.000
So what can we add, learn from toddlers?

17
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:10.000
That's what we'll be finding out in this program along with some useful new vocabulary.

18
00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:13.000
But first, I have a question for you, Beth.

19
00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:17.000
Being a toddler is certainly an important stage in a child's growth,

20
00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:20.000
but which of the following statements is true.

21
00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:24.000
A, toddlers are attracted to shapes that resemble the human body.

22
00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:29.000
B, toddlers are more active than at any other time in their lives.

23
00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:34.000
Or C, toddlers can grow up to three centimeters during sleep time.

24
00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:39.000
I think toddlers can grow up to three centimeters while asleep.

25
00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:44.000
Okay, Beth will find out if that's the correct answer later in the program.

26
00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:49.000
At two or three years old, there's not much toddlers can do for themselves.

27
00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:53.000
They depend on mum or dad to feed, clothing and care for them.

28
00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:57.000
So it's strange to think there's anything adults could learn.

29
00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:03.000
But not according to Dr. Hassan Morale, author of a new book, Sleepwell, Take Risks,

30
00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:11.000
Squish the Peas, and father to his own toddler, who spoke with BBC Radio 4 program Woman's Hour.

31
00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:15.000
When I see the toddlers by themselves, they're doing a lot of things out loud.

32
00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:18.000
Little Julie's putting on her mitts and saying, Julie can do it.

33
00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:22.000
And Colton's over on the side and he's looking down on his boots and they're on the wrong way.

34
00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:24.000
And so he says, Oh, Colton did this wrong.

35
00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:31.000
And this idea of cell tag is really a way to decrease stress in anxiety provoking situations.

36
00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:36.000
Dr. Morale observed toddlers talking to themselves out loud.

37
00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:40.000
When you talk out loud, you speak so that other people can hear you.

38
00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:44.000
But it's what the toddlers were saying that's really interesting.

39
00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:49.000
When a little girl called Julie learned how to put on her gloves, she told herself,

40
00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:55.000
Julie can do it. This is a special kind of talking out loud known as self-talk.

41
00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:00.000
Self-talk means the messages that you tell yourself and the way in which you tell them.

42
00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:06.000
It's your inner voice and in toddlers, it's usually positive and encouraging.

43
00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:12.000
Unfortunately, as we grow up, our self-talk often becomes less encouraging and more critical.

44
00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:17.000
Instead of a positive loving inner voice, as adults we tend to tell ourselves,

45
00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:20.000
you can't do it or you're no good.

46
00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:26.000
Here's Dr. Morale again explaining more to BBC Radio for Program Woman's Hour.

47
00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:29.000
We often get into the cycle of negative self-talk.

48
00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:34.000
And I think one of the best strategies that we can do is give ourselves more positive self-talk.

49
00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:39.000
So an easy way to do it is when you're down on yourself and angry with yourself,

50
00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:44.000
think about talking to yourself as a good friend, instead of actually you.

51
00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:48.000
And you'll notice that difference in how you talk to yourself.

52
00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:51.000
As an adult, you might be down on yourself.

53
00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:57.000
If you're down on yourself, you feel disappointed and self-critical about yourself.

54
00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:00.000
When this happens, your self-talk gets very negative.

55
00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:06.000
For example, telling yourself you're no good, and this can lead to a negative cycle,

56
00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:10.000
a pattern of repeating the same negative thoughts over and over again.

57
00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:16.000
This can be a problem, but not for toddlers who are naturally good at talking kindly to themselves,

58
00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.000
and celebrating the little things, like learning to get dressed.

59
00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:23.000
The solution for over critical grown-ups.

60
00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:29.000
According to Dr. Morale, pretend you're talking to a good friend, instead of to yourself, just like toddlers do.

61
00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:36.000
It seems us adults can learn something from young children after all, being kind to ourselves.

62
00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:40.000
When they're not having tantrums, toddlers really are wonderful little creatures.

63
00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:43.000
Where it reminds me of your question, Neil.

64
00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:46.000
Right, I asked you which statement about toddlers was true?

65
00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:52.000
And I said it was that toddlers can grow up to three centimeters while they sleep.

66
00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:53.000
Was I right?

67
00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:57.000
I think you know that you're not right, but that was the wrong answer.

68
00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:02.000
It's true that toddlers do grow when sleeping, but not as much as three centimeters.

69
00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:11.000
In fact, the correct answer was that being a toddler is the most active period of your whole life, which isn't hard to believe if you live with one.

70
00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:19.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned in this program about toddlers, young children who are totalling or learning to walk.

71
00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:25.000
A tantrum is a noisy, uncontrolled outburst of anger, usually from a young child.

72
00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:30.000
If you say something out loud, you say it in a way that other people can hear.

73
00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:36.000
Self-talk refers to the messages that you tell yourself and the way in which you tell them.

74
00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:38.000
It's your inner voice.

75
00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:44.000
The phrase to be down on yourself means to feel disappointed and self-critical about yourself.

76
00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:51.000
And finally, a negative cycle is a pattern of repeating the same negative thoughts over and over again.

77
00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:54.000
Something a toddler would never do.

78
00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.000
Once again, our six minutes are up.

79
00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:02.000
But remember to join us again next time for more trending topics and useful vocabulary.

80
00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:05.000
Here at 6 Minute English. Goodbye for now.
